{
  "text": "Growth media and culture conditions. F. nucleatum was grown anaerobically using a model C30 BioFlo Chemosat (New Brunswick Scientific) with a culture volume of 365 ml as described previously [CITATION_1] . Bacterial growth rates (generation times of 7-12 h) are typical of natural ecosystems such as dental plaque [CITATION_2] , and previous studies [CITATION_3] have shown that bacterial metabolic properties are often quite different when the organism is growing near its maximum growth rate (m max ). At steady state, the specific growth rate (m) is considered to be equal to the dilution rate (D) of growth medium into the culture vessel. Using the relationship T g =ln2/D, where T g is the generation time, the medium flow rate was set at 27.5 ml h 21 (D=0.075 h 21 ), which gave an estimated T g of 9.2 h. This growth rate was chosen as it equates to the expected growth rates of plaque bacteria in vivo, and we have reported previously [CITATION_4] that at low growth rates, T g =14-7 h (D=0.05 and D=0.1 h 21 respectively), the metabolic properties of F. nucleatum ATCC 10953) did not vary greatly.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "23595572",
